  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Journey on the River
  author: Lee Gyeou-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The path winds on, the long river stretches far.
    Clouds hang low over the empty plain.
    The cold cuts deep—even the migrating geese seem to suffer.
    Sand swells the waters, startling roosting gulls from sleep.
    In the forest, a pale glow flickers—ghostfire, perhaps?
    Through the rain, a fisherman's lamp shines bright.
    Our boat returns but finds no harbor in the night,
    And still the oars cry out their creaking song.
  footnotes:
    - Ghostfire (鬼火) refers to will-o'-the-wisps or mysterious phosphorescent lights seen in marshes and forests, believed in East Asian folklore to be supernatural phenomena.
    - The poem captures the melancholy and unease of a river journey in autumn or winter, blending vivid natural imagery with a sense of restless wandering.
